Fix for Adding Encryption to Your Working Template
1. Keep Your Identity Configuration (Image 2, Line ~60)
Your identity is fine, but modify it to support both:

"identity": {
  "type": "SystemAssigned,UserAssigned",
  "userAssignedIdentities": {
    "[parameters('cmkIdentity')]": {}
  }
}

2. Add These Properties to SQL Server (After administrators)
Add these two lines in your SQL Server properties section (around line 85 in Image 2):

"administrators": "[parameters('administrators')]",
"primaryUserAssignedIdentityId": "[if(parameters('infrastructureEncryptionEnabled'), parameters('cmkIdentity'), json('null'))]",
"keyId": "[if(parameters('infrastructureEncryptionEnabled'), concat(parameters('vaultBaseUrl'), '/keys/', parameters('existingKeyName')), json('null'))]"

3. Remove the Encryption Block
Delete the entire encryption block (lines ~70-85 in Image 2):


// DELETE THIS ENTIRE SECTION:
"encryption": {
  "infrastructureEncryption": "[parameters('infrastructureEncryptionEnabled')]",
  "identity": {
    "userAssignedIdentity": "[parameters('cmkIdentity')]"
  },
  "keyVaultProperties": {
    "keyName": "[parameters('existingKeyName')]",
    "keyVaultUri": "[parameters('vaultBaseUrl')]"
  }
}

4. Add Key Vault Access Policy (Before SQL Server Resource)
Add this as a separate resource before your SQL Server (around line 50):

{
  "type": "Microsoft.KeyVault/vaults/accessPolicies",
  "apiVersion": "2021-11-01-preview",
  "name": "[concat(parameters('existingKeyVaultName'), '/add')]",
  "properties": {
    "accessPolicies": [
      {
        "tenantId": "[subscription().tenantId]",
        "objectId": "[reference(parameters('cmkIdentity'), '2023-01-31').principalId]",
        "permissions": {
          "keys": [
            "get",
            "unwrapKey",
            "wrapKey"
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "condition": "[parameters('infrastructureEncryptionEnabled')]"
}

5. Update SQL Server Dependencies
In your SQL Server resource, update the dependsOn to include the access policy:

"dependsOn": [
  "[resourceId('Microsoft.KeyVault/vaults/accessPolicies', parameters('existingKeyVaultName'), 'add')]"
]

6. Complete SQL Server Properties Section Should Look Like:

"properties": {
  "version": "12.0",
  "minimalTlsVersion": "[parameters('minimalTlsVersion')]",
  "publicNetworkAccess": "[parameters('publicNetworkAccess')]",
  "administratorLogin": "[parameters('administratorLogin')]",
  "administratorLoginPassword": "[parameters('administratorLoginPassword')]",
  "administrators": "[parameters('administrators')]",
  "primaryUserAssignedIdentityId": "[if(parameters('infrastructureEncryptionEnabled'), parameters('cmkIdentity'), json('null'))]",
  "keyId": "[if(parameters('infrastructureEncryptionEnabled'), concat(parameters('vaultBaseUrl'), '/keys/', parameters('existingKeyName')), json('null'))]"
}

"cmkIdentity": {
  "type": "string",
  "defaultValue": "",
  "metadata": {
    "description": "Resource ID of user-assigned managed identity for encryption"
  }
},
"existingKeyVaultName": {
  "type": "string",
  "defaultValue": "",
  "metadata": {
    "description": "Name of existing Key Vault"
  }
},
"existingKeyName": {
  "type": "string",
  "defaultValue": "",
  "metadata": {
    "description": "Key name in Key Vault"
  }
},
"vaultBaseUrl": {
  "type": "string",
  "defaultValue": "",
  "metadata": {
    "description": "Key Vault URI"
  }
},
"infrastructureEncryptionEnabled": {
  "type": "bool",
  "defaultValue": false,
  "metadata": {
    "description": "Enable infrastructure encryption with CMK"
  }
}